Introduction

The balance between forest and agricultural land use is a critical issue, particularly in Asia, where rapid population growth and economic development place increasing pressure on natural resources. Forests play an essential role in mitigating climate change, preserving biodiversity, and supporting ecosystems, while agricultural lands are fundamental to food security and livelihoods. However, as these two land uses often compete, understanding their trends is vital for sustainable land management.

Between 2014 and 2021, global forest loss, particularly in Asia, became a significant environmental concern. According to Global Forest Watch, forest loss accelerated during this period due to deforestation, land conversion, and other anthropogenic factors. This trend raises questions about its association with expanding agricultural activities, as agriculture often necessitates the clearing of forests. Additionally, data from Resource Watch shows that agriculture remains a dominant sector of employment in many Asian countries, underscoring its critical role in regional economies and its potential impact on land use patterns.

This report examines the changes in the average forest area and agricultural area (as percentages of total land area) in Asia between 2014 and 2021. By analyzing data on these two variables, the report aims to answer the research question: How has the average forest area in Asia changed during this period compared to the average agricultural area? Insights from this analysis can contribute to understanding the trade-offs between environmental conservation and agricultural development in the region.

Research Question

How has the average forest area ( % compared to the Total Land Area) of Asia continent changed from 2014 to 2021 compared to the average Agricultural area (% compared to the Total Land Area)?

Name

We will use this short name to refer to this data set:

  • ForestArea

Data Availability

The data is available for download from:

  • Food and Agriculture Organization

Data Provenance (Purpose of Research in Data)

  • Food and Agriculture Organization collected this data from 2014 to the recent years. The data were collected to collect national data on land use (primarily focusing on agriculture, forestry, aquaculture and fisheries), irrigation and agricultural practices, annually. The data were collected by having the questionnaire in English, France, Spanish, and Russian. Data collection is carried out by country focal points, who distribute survey forms to all agencies known to conduct agricultural research in a given country, including government, nonprofit, and higher education agencies. Private-for profit sector coverage is limited, and hence excluded from this dataset.

Question that this data set could answer

  • How has the forest area ( % compared to the Total Land Area) of Asia continent changed from 2014 to 2021?

Observations

  • All agencies konwn to conduct agricultural research in a given country, including government, nonprofit, and higher education agencies. Private-for profit sector is limited and is excluded to the dataset.
  • The forest land use by total population of each particular countries
  • The private sectors are not being included in the samples, which means, the samples are not representative for the whole population since my population must included individuals from public agricultural research (government, nonprofit, and higher education agencies) and private-for-profit organizations.

Variables

  • XYear..YRYear (The value related to each year)
    • Human-readable name and description of what it represents (1 sentence): Forest_Area: This the forest area (% to the total land area) in every year since 2014 to 2021 for every countries in the world.
    • Why it matters for the question (1 sentence): This is the dependent variable for the reserach question
    • This variable includes numbers/categories/text with sample values being: Portion (in terms of percentage)
  • XYear..YRYear (The name itself)
    • Human-readable name and description of what it represents (1 sentence): Years: This is the years that recorded from 2014 to 2021
    • Why it matters for the question (1 sentence): This is the independent variable in the research questions.
    • This variable includes numbers/categories/text with sample values being: Year (2014 - 2021)
  • Country.Name
    • Human-readable name and description of what it represents (1 sentence): Countries: This is the list of countries that corresponds to the above forest area data.
    • Why it matters for the question (1 sentence): This is to use to make conclusions about Asia continents
    • This variable includes numbers/categories/text with sample values being: Countries names

Looking Forward

# Clean and ensure numeric conversion
years_filtered <- years_filtered |> 
  mutate(across(starts_with("X"), ~ suppressWarnings(as.numeric(.))))

# Calculate averages
averages <- years_filtered |> 
  summarise(
    Country.Name = "Average",

Step 4. Create a Visualization

Extract the last row of previous table. Then, create a visualization of the average Forest Area in Asian Countries from 2014-2021

library(ggplot2)

# Extract the last row of the data table
last_row <- averages[nrow(averages), ]

# Convert the last row values (excluding the 'Country.Name') to numeric
average_forest_area <- as.numeric(last_row[-1])  # Exclude the first column

# Extract the years from the column names
years <- as.numeric(gsub("X|\\.\\.YR.*", "", colnames(averages)[-1]))  # Extract numeric years

# Create a data frame for visualization plotting
average_data <- data.frame(
  Year = years,
  Average_Forest_Area = average_forest_area
)

# Calculate the linear slope score
linear_model <- lm(Average_Forest_Area ~ Year, data = average_data)  # Fit a linear model
slope <- coef(linear_model)["Year"]  # Extract the slope
slope_label <- paste("Slope:", round(slope, 3)) # Format the slope for annotation

# Plot the data
ggplot(data = average_data, aes(x = Year, y = Average_Forest_Area)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, color = "black") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red", linewidth = 1) +  # Regression line
  annotate(
    "text",
    x = mean(years),  # Position the text annotation in the middle of the x-axis range
    y = max(average_forest_area) - 1,  # Slightly below the max y-value
    label = slope_label,
    size = 5,
    color = "red"
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Average Forest Area in Asian Countries (2014 - 2021)",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Average Forest Area",
    caption = "Data source: Food and Agriculture Organization. Analysis performed in R using ggplot2."
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
  alt_text <- paste(
  "Line graph showing the average forest area in Asian countries from 2014 to 2021.",
  "The x-axis represents years (2014-2021), and the y-axis represents the average forest area as a percentage.",
  "A red line connects the yearly data points, black dots highlight specific values,",
  "and a blue linear regression line indicates a trend. The slope of the regression line is",
  round(slope, 3), ", suggesting the rate of change over time."
  )

Answering Sub-question:

  • How has the forest area ( % compared to the Total Land Area) of Asia continent changed from 2014 to 2021?

    • As seen from the visualization of the line graph extracted from Forest Area Data, the average forest area has been decreasing since 2014 to 2021. This is supported by the negative slope of -0.037 and the strong correlation between data points and negative linear trend line.

Name

We will use this short name to refer to this data set:

  • AgriculturalArea

Data Availability

The data is available for download from:

  • Food and Agriculture Organization

Data Provenance

  • Food and Agriculture Organization collected this data from 2014 to the recent years. The data were collected to collect national data on land use (primarily focusing on agriculture, forestry, aquaculture and fisheries), irrigation and agricultural practices, annually. The data were collected by having the questionnaire in English, France, Spanish, and Russian.

Question that this data set could answer

  • How has the agricultural area ( % compared to the Total Land Area) of Asia continent changed from 2014 to 2021?

Observations

  • All agencies known to conduct agricultural research in a given country, including government, nonprofit, and higher education agencies. Private-for profit sector is limited and is excluded to the data set.
  • The agricultural land use by total population of each particular countries
  • The private sectors are not being included in the samples, which means, the samples are not representative for the whole population since my population must included individuals from public agricultural research (government, nonprofit, and higher education agencies) and private-for-profit organizations.

Variables

  • XYear..YRYear (The value associated with each year)
    • Human-readable name and description of what it represents (1 sentence): Argricultural_Area: This the agricultural area (% to the total land area) in every year since 2014 to 2021 for every countries in the world.
    • Why it matters for the question (1 sentence): This is the dependent variable for the reserach question
    • This variable includes numbers/categories/text with sample values being: Portion (in terms of percentage)
  • XYear..YRYear (The year itself)
    • Human-readable name and description of what it represents (1 sentence): Years: This is the years that recorded from 2014 to 2021
    • Why it matters for the question (1 sentence): This is the independent variable in the research questions.
    • This variable includes numbers/categories/text with sample values being: Year (2014 - 2021)
  • Country.Name
    • Human-readable name and description of what it represents (1 sentence): Countries: This is the list of countries that corresponds to the above agricultural area data.
    • Why it matters for the question (1 sentence): This is to use to make conclusions about Asia continents
    • This variable includes numbers/categories/text with sample values being: Countries names

Looking Forward

  • Using mutate to create new columns for Year. Combines countries in Asia continents and average out the agricultural area data from every countries. Make a graph comparing agricultural area data in Asia continents with time (in years).

Combining two data visualization (Line Graph):

The line graph visualizations from two data sets are used to combine to answer the research question:

library(ggplot2)

# Data preparation
forest_area_data <- data.frame(
  Year = years,
  Metric = "Average Forest Area",
  Value = average_forest_area
)

agricultural_area_data <- data.frame(
  Year = c(2014, 2021),
  Metric = "Agricultural Area",
  Value = c(
    mean(scatter_data$Agricultural_Area_2014),
    mean(scatter_data$Agricultural_Area_2021)
  )
)

# Combine both datasets
combined_data <- rbind(forest_area_data, agricultural_area_data)

# Calculate linear regression and correlation for forest area
forest_model <- lm(Value ~ Year, data = forest_area_data)
forest_slope <- round(coef(forest_model)["Year"], 3)
forest_correlation <- round(cor(forest_area_data$Year, forest_area_data$Value), 3)

# Calculate linear regression and correlation for agricultural area
agriculture_model <- lm(Value ~ Year, data = agricultural_area_data)
agriculture_slope <- round(coef(agriculture_model)["Year"], 3)
agriculture_correlation <- round(cor(agricultural_area_data$Year, agricultural_area_data$Value), 3)

# Plot
ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = Year, y = Value, color = Metric)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +  # Data points
  geom_smooth(
    data = forest_area_data,
    aes(x = Year, y = Value),
    method = "lm",
    se = FALSE,
    color = "blue",
    linetype = "dashed"
  ) +  # Regression line for forest area
  geom_smooth(
    data = agricultural_area_data,
    aes(x = Year, y = Value),
    method = "lm",
    se = FALSE,
    color = "red",
    linetype = "dashed"
  ) +  # Regression line for agricultural area
  annotate(
    "text",
    x = 2017, y = max(forest_area_data$Value),
    label = paste("Forest Area\nSlope =", forest_slope),
    color = "blue",
    size = 4
  ) +
  annotate(
    "text",
    x = 2017, y = max(agricultural_area_data$Value),
    label = paste("Agricultural Area\nSlope =", agriculture_slope),
    color = "red",
    size = 4
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Trend Analysis of Forest and Agricultural Areas (2014-2021)",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Percentage",
    color = "Metric",
    caption = "Dashed lines represent linear regression. Slope and R values are annotated."
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "top"
  )

Combining two data visualization (Bar Graph):

The bar graphs visualizations from two data sets are used to combine to answer the research question:

library(ggplot2)

# Data preparation for forest area
forest_area_data <- data.frame(
  Year = years,
  Metric = "Average Forest Area",
  Value = average_forest_area
)

# Data preparation for agricultural area
agricultural_area_data <- data.frame(
  Year = c(2014, 2021),
  Metric = "Agricultural Area",
  Value = c(
    mean(scatter_data$Agricultural_Area_2014),
    mean(scatter_data$Agricultural_Area_2021)
  )
)

# Combine the data for both metrics into one dataset
bar_plot_data <- rbind(forest_area_data, agricultural_area_data)

# Ensure 'Year' is numeric or character for filtering
bar_plot_data$Year <- as.numeric(as.character(bar_plot_data$Year))

# Filter the data for only 2014 and 2021
filtered_data <- subset(bar_plot_data, Year %in% c(2014, 2021))

# Plot the bar graph
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = factor(Year), y = Value, fill = Metric)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge", color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Comparison of Forest and Agricultural Areas (2014 and 2021)",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Percentage",
    fill = "Metric",
    caption = "Bar chart showing forest and agricultural area percentages in 2014 and 2021."
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "top"
  )

Answer the Research Question:

  • Based on the first visualization, the two datasets were combined to provide insights into the research question. The forest area data exhibits a strong correlation with a negative linear trend, as indicated by the slope and data points over the years. This suggests that the average forest area in Asian countries has been steadily decreasing from 2014 to 2021. In contrast, the agricultural area data shows a strong positive correlation, with a linear trend line slope of 0.061 and a perfect correlation value of 1. This indicates a consistent increase in the average agricultural area over the same period.

  • Based on the second visualization of bar graphs, the inverse relationship between forest area and agricultural area is evident even with a small amount. The decline in forest area coinciding with the rise in agricultural area may imply that land conversion from forests to agricultural use is occurring.

  • Overall, while the forest area data highlights a decline in forest coverage, the agricultural area data points to a growth in agricultural land use across Asian countries from 2014 to 2021.

Further Research:

  • The inverse relationship between forest area and agricultural area suggests a potential association between these two variables. Further research is needed to explore this connection in detail. It is hypothesized that as forest area decreases over time, agricultural area increases. This trend may be driven by population growth, which leads to greater demand for food and consequently, an expansion of agricultural land. This expansion often comes at the expense of forested regions, contributing to a reduction in the worldâs finite forest resources.
